Trends in travel prices since 1989
Up to 1989, only five public tourist agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourist agencies at that time mainly sold tours to the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which resulted in considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The greater paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation from that country was necessary; another individual travel was impossible.
At the time, tourist agencies offered trips to the West, but they had to either stand up all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
A currency permit was needed for a trip to the West, and it was not issued to politically untrustworthy people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a currency.
Most of the Czechs have taken their vacation home, which has resulted in a large number of cats and summer homes, and this habit is still today.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus survived the current revolution.
