The great paradox that we no longer realize is that by 1989 we could not freely visit Croatia's most popular at present, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need for visas in the neighbouring Western European countries had been lifted, and this was the beginning of a huge wave of short journeys mainly in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't have taken any trips to the West, and they all wanted to go there for a while.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, since their income at the time did not catch up with the hotel or the pension.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring their own food (conservations, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important moment is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown. After decades our tourists can finally buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and our average income grew, leading to another important situation in 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourist agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines; compared to the past, aircraft have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the possibility of ordering discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
