But suddenly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who are just looking for a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, researchers and politicians use the website to study the world wide, from health issues to social trends expressed in 'Laika', wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, adding on average three entries per day, Facebook's "super-current information" is a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles entitled 800 per cent in the title over the past five years.
